<br>
I started these while leader of Divindi, continued when I was unguilded, and will continue to do so while a member of Apex. These are not Apex raids, they are MY raids. <br>
I have never had more than three raids on the calendar at any time. <br>
<br>
While Divindi was around, I would count these raids as guild raids, and ensure that Divindi as a whole had no more than three active reservations.<br>
<br>
As Aenae said, these raids make it possible for people in smaller guilds to get their armor.  If it weren't for open raids, I think a lot of people would be missing out on a very fun part of the game. It is also way to meet a lot of new people, work together helping each other, and a fun way to spend an evening.<br>
<br>
I think people's main concern is how it impacts the calendar. *sigh*<br>
<br>
I have as much right as any guild to make a reservation, seeing as how I have every intention of fulfilling it. <br>
<br>
I fully expect to get flamed here, saying that Apex has reservations, and I have reservations, and that it is abuse.<br>
<br>
If you intend to flame me, continue reading. If you don't, skip to the next set of asterisks.<br>
**************************************************<br>
The answer is..../bonk you<br>
<br>
Apex raids are for Apex guild members. <br>
<br>
My raids are for anyone. I am not representing my guild, nor am I getting loot specifically for the guild. <br>
<br>
If you can't see the difference, then you are being deliberately obtuse. <br>
<br>
end rant<br>
